Introduction

Per the instruction, in this project, Im going to utilize the data in World Banks database and discover possible relations with the outcome variable poverty. To predict poverty, Im going to include the following measurement:

  • Unemployment Rate
  • % of population has Access to Electricity
  • Renewable Energy Consumption % of total energy consumption
  • Birth Rate
  • Children Mortality Rate
  • Literacy Rate

Unemployment Rate represents a countrys current economic status. When a country is in bad situation, like in depression, then a lot of people are not likely to find jobs and thus will live in poverty. This should have positive relation with poverty.

% of population has Access to Electricity represents a conutrys development status in terms of energy. Generally, a well developed conutry should allow almost all citizens to have access to electricity, as it is basically the standard of modernity. I expect this has negative relation with poverty.

Renewable Energy Consumption % of total energy consumption represents a countrys development in energy further. Renewable energy such as solar energy and wind power is expensive than fossil energy. Only those countries that are very well developed will have the money to spend on renewable energy.

Birth rate from another perspective measures a conutrys development. Generally, developing country will tend to have high birth rate because their children are a type of resources, representing labor. They will tend to have more labor force to help out the family. In a developed country, birth rate tend to low because its costly to raise a baby. This should have negative relation with poevrty.

Children Mortality Rate is a proxy of a conutrys medical level. In a conutry with sufficient and affordable medical treatment, the children mortality rate should be low. But in countries where there are a lot of poor people, it is less likely that this country has a lot of medical resources and their children will tend to die early. This should have positive relation with poverty.

Literacy Rate measures a conutrys educational resources and percentage of peoples access to good occupation. A high literacy rate tends to represent a lot of people are educated, and educated people tend to find a job that can support themselves, and less likely to be poor. This rate is expected to be negatively related to poverty.

In this project I will focus with unemployment rate, but if any interesting outcome pops up I will also dig into it.

The first two, poverty_headcount_ratio and poverty_headcount_ratio_1.90 are different measures of the poverty. First one represents the poverty rate accordind to that countrys standard. The second one is the rate according to an international standard the percentage of the population living on less than $1.90 a day at 2011 international prices(World Bank).

The rest are the predictor variables. The comments explain what they are meant for.

Download data

wb_data <- wb(country = "all", indicator = wb_variables,
              startdate = 2007, enddate = 2018, return_wide = TRUE)

wb_recent <- wb_data %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  arrange(desc(date)) %>%
  fill(wb_variables) %>% # fill NAs with value from most recent year
  drop_na() %>%
  top_n(n = 1, wt = date) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  rename_at(vars(wb_variables), ~ wb_names)


nrow(wb_recent)
## [1] 115

First two blocks we download the data using wb, and then sort the data and pick out the most recent one in each country. From nrow(wb_rent) we see that there are 113 total number of data. This establishes that we have enough samples and can assume the samples are at random.

Analysis 1.

Analyze the data first with poverty_headcount_ratio_1.90 the first outcome variable.

Analysis of poverty_headcount_ratio_1.90 simple model

First comes the simple linear model with only one predictor unemp_rate.

# Create the Models 
# Simple Model
linear_model_simple = lm(poverty_headcount_ratio_1.90~unemp_rate, data =wb_recent)
summary(linear_model_simple)

## F-statistic: 3.758 on 1 and 113 DF,  p-value: 0.05504

From summary(linear_model_simple), the estimated coefficient of unemp_rate umemployment rate is -0.6546. A negative coefficient is against the expectation. This numbers means that an increase of unemployment rate of 1% will lead to a decrease of poverty rate of 0.65%, which is very conuter-intuitive. Before fitting the data, the expectation is an increase in umployment rate will increase the poverty rate. But this turns out not the case. After some consideration, this might be due to

  • Umployment status does not directly mean this person is poor. From economics 101, umployment can be temporal, and a person who has savings but is unemployed is not poor
  • The poverty measurement is an international standard, in countries with good national welfare such as Swiss and Dutch, even though a person is unemployed, it is possible that living with national welfare is not in poverty standard. In contrary, a people born in a less developed country, even he is employed, it is possible that he is in poverty
  • In less developed country, the unemployment status may be not well recored. And probably many people do not register that they are employed, or they are doing not registered job still get paid.
  • Measurement error on unemployment rate

confint(linear_model_simple)
##                 2.5 %      97.5 %
## (Intercept) 16.185191 28.85876432
## unemp_rate  -1.237929  0.01343626

Checking the confint(linear_model_simple) we see a loose confidence intervals. On one right side, in terms of %, a -0.02 decrease in poverty rate percentage actually does not have much impact on the outcome. On the left side -1.2 is huge relatively. The confidence interval is too wide to reach practical siginificance conclusion.

This further explains the low p-value 0.0426 of the unemp_rate, and why a confidence intverval is better than hypothesis test. The hypothesis test only tells us to reject the null, which means this coefficient is not 0 at a 5% significance level. 

autoplot(linear_model_simple)

Cheking the 4 plots its clear that the simple model has a lot of problems.

From Residuals vs Fitted its clear that the residuals have a nonlinear relation with fitted value. The simple model does not fit well. This is in line with the ~0.03 r-square score.

From Normal Q-Q , the residuals are not at the 45 degree line. They are in a s-shaped, and claerly not normally distributed. They have more of a bell shape curve like t distribution

From Scale-Location, its actually not bad and we cannot say the model has much heteroskadacity in terms of real-world data

From Residuals vs Leverage we see there are quite a few outliers

Summary of simple model

To summarize, the model is coarse but not a bad start. Statistically, the ~0.04 p-value allows us to reject the null hypothesis. But practically, along with the confidence interval, we cannot reach practical conclusion. Also, the diagnostic plots demonstrates the residuals are not normally distributed. This warns us to trust the model less because our statistical inferences are based on the assumption that the residuals are nearly normally distributed.

To interpret the coeffcient, an increase of unemployment rate of 1 % would lead to a decrease of population in poverty 0.65%.

Looking at the p-value, we reject the null hypothesis for coefficients of renew_eng_consp_rate, birth_rate and literacy_rate. And notably we cannot reject the null for unemp_rate, the unemployment rate. This means that in the complex model, the unemployment rate has no correlation with poverty rate at a 5% significance level, keeping other factors constant. Although the esimate is still negative, as we cannot reject the null rightnow, that becomes not that important. This is further illustrated below with confidence interval. The adjusted r-square of the model is 0.819, that is pretty good, maybe too good for real world data.

Taking a closer look at their confidence interval:

confint(linear_model)
##                              2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept)          -22.116718530 93.0788329
## unemp_rate            -0.352017701  0.2641064

## life_exp              -0.796421122  0.5444200

We see the confidence interval of unemployment rate ranges from negative to positive. This menas that the true unemployment rate coefficient can be postive and negative. Thus with the complex model, it further illustrates why the negative coefficient obtained in the simple model is not meaningful, since it bounces between negative and positive. From this point, statistically we see there is no (linear) correlation between unemployment rate and poverty rate, keeping other factors consant. Practically there is no significance either.

Other predictors

Along with confidence interval, we can clearly see that access to eletricity indeed has practical significance to poverty. Its confidence interval is narrow restricted around -0.67 and -0.42. Either -0.42 and -0.67 both have practical effect on decrease of poverty rate. Taking a look on the units, tt means one 1% increase in % of population has access to electricity decreases 0.42% or 0.67% of poverty population. And the correlation between electricity and poverty may be due to:

  • Access to electricity is a very basic, necessary and important requirement for people. A government with money first thing will do is probably to develop electricity supply
  • Measurement of Access to eletricity is a long-term factor and connot be changed in a few years, unlike unemployment rate. Poverty is also a long-term factor. The change in electricity fits the change of poverty rate well

Aside from electricity, other predictors do not demonstrate very influential effect. For birth_rate and childmort, we cannot even reject the null hypothesis. From a statistical standpoint, this is probably because the correlation of acs_to_elec is so strong that other predictors are trivial in comparison. Trying to explain it in a more practical way:

  • birth_rate: there could be developed countries that have not low birth rates such as U.S. and China, this bias the prediction
  • childmort: as long as a conutry is somewhat developed, the childmort will decrease very quick and to almost zero, the relation between childmort and poverty may not be linear

autoplot(linear_model)

From Residuals vs Fitted, we see the residuals are clustered when fitted value is small. But generally there is no obvious non-linear pattern

From Normal Q-Q the residuals are more s-shaped. This implies the residuals are more in a bell-shaped distribution.

From Scale-Location, the residuals do seem come from two center point with two variance and in this model it does seem heteroskadacity.

From Residuals vs Leverage we see no obvious outliers

Summary of complex model

In summary, we can neither find correlation between unemployment rate and poverty rate at this point, and nor practical significance on unemployment rate. Also, the diagnostic plots show the model has two problems: 1) residuals not normally distributed, 2) heteroskadacity. Thus again we shall not trust the inferences that much. For e.g., heteroskadacity means the data do not only has one variance, but in the linear regression we did we assumed they have only one. The coefficient predicted may not be that accurate.

Conclusion

In conclusion, there is neither statistical (linear) correlation between unemployment rate and poverty rate and nor practical significance, summarizing from above analysis. But the esimated, negative coefficient does at the first time surprised me a little bit. And this is against my initial thought on unemployment rate.

And throughout the process of fitting the complete models, I discovered that the access to electricity is the major indicator to poverty. Some other initial thought hold some dont, as indicated above on the other predictors analysis of complex model on poverty_headcount_ratio_1.90.

What biases the analysis the most is probably the way we fill na items. We fill the na item by the most recent years one. This can be biased up or down, depending on the trend of that column and the truth. Whats better is probably to use a sample mean or regression to estimate it.

No correlation between unemployment rate and poverty rate does not necessarily mean no causation. As correlation is only for linear model. However, with these observational data, we are still unable to reach causation. To reach causation we need to rule out all the possible confounder. But for a socio-economic data as such, its impossible to rule out all the confounder because in real life they have too many underlying correlations with other factors. Thus we need more information, like a control study, to reach a causal conclusion

Lastly, its very beneficial and insightful to try to find good predictors and do analysis on them. I deeply understand its very tempted to add a bunch of predictors to see the r-square go up. But that will in turn make the model very very hard to explain. The reasoning behind why one coefficient not work as expected will be much harder to think through. And in that case it will have little pracitcal usage and impractical to use it to predict the future outcome.
